{XPPMATH 20 "6(\"\"\"\"\"&\"#5F%F$F#" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "
6)\"\"\"\"\"'\"#:\"#?F%F$F#" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6*\"\"\"
\"\"(\"#@\"#NF&F%F$F#" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6+\"\"\"\"\")\"
#G\"#c\"#qF&F%F$F#" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6,\"\"\"\"\"*\"#O
\"#%)\"$E\"F'F&F%F$F#" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }
}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 214 "3.  Fu
nctions.  In this exericse we study the basic properties of polynomial
s and rational functions.  Some revelant MAPLE commands will be   fact
or, expand, solve, fsolve, denom, numer, simplify, subs,   ....... ." 
}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 171 "     The first thing we need to learn \+
is how to define a function.  There are two ways, each with its own ad
vantages and disadvantages.  First define the polynomial p1 as " }
{TEXT 282 2 "a " }{TEXT -1 1 "s" }{TEXT 283 23 "ymbolic expression in \+
x" }{TEXT -1 119 " in the following way:    p1:=x^2-1;  (Note the colo
n before the =, this is always required when defining something.)  " }
}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 10 "p1:=x^2-1;" }}{PARA 11 "" 
1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#>%#p1G,&*$)%\"xG\"\"#\"\"\"F*F*!\"\"" }}}{PARA 0 "
" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 39 "     Now define th
e same polynomial as " }{TEXT 281 30 "an operation on the variable x" 
}{TEXT -1 40 " in the following way:     p2:=x->x^2-1;" }}{PARA 0 "" 
0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 13 "p2:=x->
x^2-1;" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#>%#p2Gf*6#%\"xG6\"6$%)operat
orG%&arrowGF(,&*$)9$\"\"#\"\"\"F1F1!\"\"F(F(F(" }}}{PARA 257 "" 0 "" 
